Let $$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {{{{e^x} - 1} \over x},} &amp; {x &gt; 0}  \cr 
   {0,} &amp; {x = 0}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$ be a real valued function. Which one of the following statements is correct?

en.explanation:
Given, $$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {{{{e^x} - 1} \over x},} &amp; {x &gt; 0}  \cr 
   {0,} &amp; {x = 0}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = {{x{d \over {dx}}({e^x} - 1) - ({e^x} - 1){d \over {dx}}(x)} \over {{x^2}}}$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = {{x({e^x} - 0) - ({e^x} - 1)} \over {{x^2}}}$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = {{x{e^x} - {e^x} + 1} \over {{x^2}}}$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = {{{e^x}(x - 1) + 1} \over {{x^2}}}$$<br><br>Clearly, f'(x) &gt; 0, x &gt; 0<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is a strictly increasing function in (0, x).

